{"title_page": "King Kong Bundy", "text_new": "{{short description|American deceased professional wrestler actor and stand-up comedian}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = King Kong Bundy\n|image       = Kingkondbundy.jpg\n|caption     = King Kong Bundy in 1995\n|alt         =\n|birth_name  = Christopher Alan Pallies<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1955|11|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Woodbury, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_place     = [[Glassboro, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2019|03|04|1955|11|7}}\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Marcy Russell|1994|2002|reason=divorced}}\n|children    = 1\n|names       = Big Daddy Bundy<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><br>Boom Boom Bundy<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web |title=King Kong Bundy profile |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/k/king-kong-bundy.html |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref><br>Chris Bundy<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><br>Chris Cannon<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><br>Chris Canyon<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><ref name=\"Myers1999\"/><br>Crippler Cannon<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>King Kong Bundy<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/><br>Man Mountain Cannon, Jr<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|height      = 6 ft 4 in<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|weight      = 458 lb<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|billed      = [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]]<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/><ref name=\"Shields2010\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|debut       = March 7, 1981<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|retired     = May 2007<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n}}\n'''Christopher Alan Pallies''' (November 7, 1955 \u2013 March 4, 2019) was an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], actor and [[stand-up comedian]], better known by his [[ring name]], '''King Kong Bundy'''. He appeared in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) in the mid-1980s and mid-1990s and wrestled in the main event of [[WrestleMania 2]] in 1986, facing  [[Hulk Hogan]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage match]] for the [[WWE Championship|WWF World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"Grasso2014\">{{cite book |last=Grasso |first=John |date=2014 |title=Historical Dictionary of Wrestling |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]] |isbn=978-0-8108-7926-3 |pages=55\u201356 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KUsJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 }}</ref><ref name=\"WWEBio\">{{cite web |title=King Kong Bundy |publisher=[[WWE]] |url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/kingkongbundy |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Shields2010\">{{cite book |last=Shields |first=Brian |date=2010 |title=Main Event: WWE in the Raging 80s |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=978-1-4516-0467-2 |pages=80\u201381 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ktv7Nj2C9QUC&pg=PA80}}</ref><ref name=\"Hornbaker2017\">{{cite book |last=Hornbaker |first=Tim |date=2017 |title=Legends of Pro Wrestling: 150 Years of Headlocks, Body Slams, and Piledrivers |publisher=[[Skyhorse Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-61321-875-4 |pages=956\u2013957 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UuGLDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT957}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Woodbury, New Jersey]], on November 7, 1955,<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"NYT Death\">{{cite web |last=Slotnik |first=Daniel E. |date=March 5, 2019 |title=King Kong Bundy, Gargantuan Professional Wrestler, Dies at 63 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/05/obituaries/king-kong-bundy-dead.html |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref> Pallies attended [[Washington Township High School (New Jersey)|Washington Township High School]] in [[Sewell, New Jersey]], graduating in 1973.<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Beym2010\">{{cite web |last=Beym |first=Jessica |date=January 28, 2010 |title=Former professional wrestling star to visit Washington Township to promote hoagie sale |publisher=[[Advance Publications]] |work=[[NJ.com]] |url=http://www.nj.com/gloucester-county/index.ssf/2010/01/former_professional_wrestling.html |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref> He had two sisters and three brothers.<ref name=\"NYT Death\" />\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career (1981\u20131985)===\nPallies was trained to wrestle by [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]] at the \"Monster Factory\" in [[Bellmawr, New Jersey]]. He debuted on March 7, 1981, wrestling for the World Wrestling Federation under the ring name \"Chris Canyon\".<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Myers1999\">{{cite book |last=Myers |first=Robert |year=1999 |title=The Professional Wrestling Trivia Book |publisher=Branden Books |isbn=0-8283-2045-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/professionalwres0000myer/page/4 4,49] |url=https://archive.org/details/professionalwres0000myer/page/4 }}</ref> In the early years of his career, he also used the name \"Chris Cannon\".<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Pallies relocated to [[Texas]], where he joined the [[World Class Championship Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\">{{cite book |last=Meltzer |first=Dave |author-link=Dave Meltzer |year=1986 |title=The Wrestling Observer's Who's who in Pro Wrestling |work=[[Wrestling Observer]] |page=28 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-rFZAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> He was developed by the [[Von Erich family]] as \"Big Daddy Bundy\" (after [[Shirley Crabtree]]'s \"Big Daddy\" moniker).<ref>{{cite web |date=October 7, 2013 |title=The 50 greatest ring names ever |publisher=WWE |url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-greatest-ring-names-ever/page-17 |accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> He wore blue jeans with a rope belt. After a dispute with the Von Erich family, Bundy was recruited by [[Gary Hart (wrestler)|\"Playboy\" Gary Hart]] and dramatically reintroduced as \"King Kong Bundy\", with the \"Big Daddy\" portion of his moniker replaced by the name of cinematic monster, [[King Kong]], wearing the black singlet for the first time to signify his change. He lost his hair during the feud, adding to his signature look.\n\nBundy was [[Fritz Von Erich]]'s opponent for Fritz's 1982 [[Professional wrestling match types#Retirement match|retirement match]] at the [[Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show]] held at the [[Texas Stadium]].<ref name=FritzVonErichRetirement>{{cite web |date=June 4, 1982 |title=Texas Stadium 1982 Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show |publisher=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/misc/wccw/misccards.html#82 |accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=RetirementAlmanak>{{cite news |title=Historical Cards: Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show (June 4, 1982. Irving, Texas) |work=PWI Presents: 2007 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts |publisher=Kappa Publications |id=2007 Edition |page=172}}</ref>\n\nHe also competed in various territories such as the [[American Wrestling Association]] and [[National Wrestling Alliance]]. He also had a tendency to demand a five-count (as opposed to the usual three count) for [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfalls]] whenever he dominated his opponent in a [[Squash (professional wrestling)|squash]] match, a [[List of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] he began while wrestling for [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Mid-South Wrestling]]. During this time Bundy also wrestled in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] often teaming with [[Rick Rude]] and [[Jim Neidhart]] against opponents such as [[Jerry Lawler]].\n\n===World Wrestling Federation (1985\u20131988)===\n====WWF Championship pursuit (1985\u20131986) ====\n[[File:Andre the Giant.jpg|thumb|Bundy and [[Big John Studd]] facing [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]] and [[Hillbilly Jim]]]]\nAfter making a few appearances on [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]/[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] joint shows in early 1985, Bundy officially debuted in the WWF on the March 16, 1985 airing of ''[[WWF Championship Wrestling]]'', defeating [[Mario Mancini]].<ref name=WWF6389Book>{{cite book |last=Cawthon |first=Graham |year=2013 |title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 1: WWF 1963 - 1989 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1492825975}}</ref> First managed by [[Jimmy Hart]], he was immediately [[Push (professional wrestling)|pushed]] with dominating victories over all of his opponents. Bundy also reprised his gimmick of demanding a five-count from the referee while pinning an opponent, to show how badly he had beaten his hapless opponent.<ref name=WWF6389Book/> He defeated [[Conrad Efraim|S.D. \"Special Delivery\" Jones]] in what was announced as only nine seconds at the [[WrestleMania I|first WrestleMania]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] (it was actually about 17 seconds).<ref name=\"Bundy/Jones\">{{cite web |last=Clapp |first=John |date=April 3, 2012 |title=10 Show of Show Shorties: Return to sender |publisher=[[WWE]] |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/29/fastest-wrestlemania-matches/page-6 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> This remained the shortest match in [[WrestleMania]] history until 2008 when [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Chavo Guerrero Jr.]] in a legitimate eight seconds at [[WrestleMania XXIV]].<ref name=\"slam\">{{cite web |last=Plummer |first=Dale |date=March 30, 2008 |title=Mayweather, Orton survive Mania; Edge, Flair don't |publisher=SLAM! Sports|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/31/5148416.html |accessdate=April 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1985, Hart traded Bundy to manager [[Bobby Heenan]] in exchange for [[Adrian Adonis]] and [[the Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]].<ref name=WWF6389Book/> After joining [[the Heenan Family]], Bundy feuded extensively with [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], a feud which started during an [[List of professional wrestling terms#A|angle]] where Bundy interfered in one of Andr\u00e9's matches and delivered several splashes, giving the Giant a [[kayfabe]] broken [[Human sternum|sternum]].<ref name=WWF6389Book/> They feuded for several months, including a pair of tag team matches on ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event II]]'' and ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event III|III]]'' in late 1985, where Bundy, and Andr\u00e9's other nemesis, [[Big John Studd]], first faced Andr\u00e9 and [[Tony Atlas]] and then Andr\u00e9 and [[WWF World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night's Main Event #2 results |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#2 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night's Main Event #3 results |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#3 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> On September 23, 1985, Bundy faced Andr\u00e9 the Giant at [[Madison Square Garden]] in a match billed as \"the Colossal Jostle\". Andr\u00e9 dominated the match, with the match ending after Big John Studd came from the locker rooms to Bundy's aid and attacked the Giant, causing a disqualification.<ref name=HolyGround>{{cite book |last=Cawthon |first=Graham |editor-last=Sawyer |editor-first=Grant |date=November 26, 2014 |title=Holy Ground: 50 Years of WWE at Madison Square Garden (The History of Professional Wrestling) |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-5052292-6-4 |chapter=1980s |pages=130\u2013246}}</ref>\n\nBundy also began targeting Hogan and the WWF World Championship in late 1985. At ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event V]]'', Hogan was dominating challenger [[Don Muraco|the Magnificent Muraco]] when Bundy (with Heenan in tow) ran to ambush Hogan. With Muraco's help, Bundy repeatedly gave Hogan [[Professional wrestling attacks#Body avalanche|avalanches]] and [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big splash|big splash]]es, which caused Hogan to severely bruise his ribs (kayfabe). Bundy demanded a match and claimed Hogan was afraid of him, setting up their [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night Main Event - Mar. 1, 1986 |publisher=History of WWE |url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/snme.htm |accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> Hogan demanded revenge and agreed to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage]] match for the WWF World Heavyweight Championship as the main event of [[WrestleMania 2]] in the [[Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena|Los Angeles]] portion of the event, which Hogan won.<ref>{{cite web |last=Powell |first=John |title=WrestleMania 2: Caged Heat |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania20/WrestleMania2.html |accessdate=November 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==== Various feuds (1986\u20131988) ====\nLater in 1986, Bundy reformed his tag-team partnership with Studd and began a feud with [[The Machines (professional wrestling)|The Machines]], [[Bill Eadie]] and [[Blackjack Mulligan]] wrestling under masks (as the Super Machine and Big Machine, respectively) and often joined by Andre the Giant (as the Giant Machine). The storyline was that Bundy and Studd, along with Heenan, claimed that the Giant Machine was a masked Andre the Giant, and was competing under the mask and alias to circumvent an earlier suspension (due to no-showing for an event), but none of them ever proved that Andre and the Giant Machine were one and the same. Eventually, Bundy and Studd began teaming up with Heenan in a series of six-man tag team matches against the Machines (usually, Big and Super; as Andre's health was starting to deteriorate at this time, the Giant Machine made occasional appearances, but more often than not, it was either Captain [[Lou Albano]] or a number of popular faces\u2014often, Hogan, [[Roddy Piper]] and others\u2014who teamed with the other Machines). Bundy and Studd were regularly beaten, but won their last match over the Super-Big version of the Machines at Madison Square Garden. Also in the latter half of 1986, Bundy and Studd received shots at the WWF Tag Team Championship against [[The British Bulldogs]], but were unsuccessful, often losing by disqualification. Studd left the WWF shortly after their last match with the Machines, and Bundy went back to singles competition.\n\nAt [[WrestleMania III]], Bundy was involved in a mixed six-man tag team match, teaming up with [[Midget professional wrestler|midget wrestlers]] [[Shigeri Akabane|Little Tokyo]] and [[Eric Tovey|Lord Littlebrook]] against [[Hillbilly Jim]], the [[Raymond Kessler|Haiti Kid]] and [[Lionel Giroux|Little Beaver]]. During the match, after being pestered by Beaver, Bundy body-slammed him and delivered a big elbow, causing his team's disqualification and his own tag partners to turn against him.<ref name=\"WM III\">{{cite news|title=WrestleMania III Results|publisher=WWE|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm3/results/|accessdate=February 14, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Main Event: WWE in the Raging 80s|last=Shields|first=Brian|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2006|isbn=1-4165-3257-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/mainevent00bria/page/81 81]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mainevent00bria/page/81}}</ref> At the [[King of the Ring (1987)|1987 King of the Ring]] on September 4, Bundy made it to the finals of the [[King of the Ring tournament]], where he was defeated by [[Randy Savage]]. In November 1987, Bundy defeated Hulk Hogan via a count-out on an episode of ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XIII]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#13|title=Saturday Night's Main Event #13 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> but lost to Hogan in a rematch on the next episode of the series;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#14|title=Saturday Night's Main Event #14 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> the match was best known for the referee becoming legitimately injured when he was accidentally caught between Hogan and a charging Bundy, and Andre the Giant's post-match attack of Hogan shortly after Bundy left ringside. Although no longer appearing on the WWF's syndicated TV shows, Bundy continued to wrestle house shows in early 1988 (often losing to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]]); his last match during his initial WWF run was a televised match at [[Madison Square Garden]] in February 1988, teaming up with One Man Gang in a loss to [[Don Muraco]] and [[The Ultimate Warrior]].\n\n=== Semi-retirement (1988\u20131994) ===\nAfter leaving the WWF in 1988, Bundy went into semi-retirement, wrestling only a handful of matches. In 1993, he wrestled in the main event of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]]'s inaugural [[November to Remember#1993|November to Remember]] [[Card (sports)#Supercard|supercard]], appearing as the mystery tag team partner of [[Terry Funk]] in a losing effort against [[Road Warrior Hawk]] and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]]. On May 13, 1994, Bundy defeated [[The Godfather (wrestler)|Papa Shango]] at NWA New Jersey. In the summer of 1994 he made a couple of appearances for [[United States Wrestling Association]].\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation (1994\u20131995) ===\nBundy returned to the WWF in the fall of 1994 as a member of [[Ted DiBiase]]'s [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Stable|stable]], [[The Million Dollar Corporation]].<ref name=WWF9099Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 2: WWF 1990 - 1999  | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2013 | asin=B00RWUNSRS}}</ref><ref name=\"Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/m/million-dollar-corporation.html|title=Million Dollar Corporation profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> He had a successful [[pay-per-view]] return at the [[Survivor Series (1994)|Survivor Series]], when he and fellow \"Million Dollar Team\" member Bam Bam Bigelow survived a match against [[Lex Luger]]'s \"Guts and Glory\" team.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Bundy was then billed as a favorite in the [[Royal Rumble (1995)|1995 Royal Rumble]], but lasted only three minutes before being eliminated by another big man, [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Rumble 1995 Elimination Info|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble2.html#95|accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> Bundy made his return to WrestleMania at [[WrestleMania XI]], where [[Undefeated WrestleMania streak of The Undertaker|he was defeated]] by [[the Undertaker]],<ref name=WWF9099Book/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania20/WrestleMania11.html|title=No worse WrestleMania than 11|author=Powell, John|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=November 8, 2009}}</ref> Bundy was later pushed down the card before being released in October 1995 after teaming with [[The Godfather (wrestler)|Kama]] losing to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] and [[Henry O. Godwinn]] for a dark match for [[WWF Superstars of Wrestling]].\n\n===Independent circuit and retirement (1995\u20132007)===\n{{more|Heroes of Wrestling}}\nAfter leaving the WWF in late 1995,<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Bundy wrestled for several independent promotions in the United States. In April 1997, he resurfaced in magazines when he joined a faction managed by [[Kenny Casanova]] called \"Camp Casanova\" along with \"Danger\" Dave DeJohn and the Masked Maniac at times in USWF, NBW, and USA Power Pro Wrestling. In a match against \"the Seven Foot Tall\" Primo Canera III, Bundy knee-dropped his opponent and then \"Bundy-splashed\" him. The impact actually broke the ring, leaving the two grapplers in a pit in the center of the squared circle. This independent footage was picked up by ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]''.\n\nHis feuds against [[Jimmy Snuka|\"Superfly\" Jimmy Snuka]], [[Doink the Clown]], and [[Tom Brandi]] were among many main events in the northeast independent circuit. In 1999, at the Kolf Arena in [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]] he won the [[WSL World Heavyweight Championship|AWA Superstars of Wrestling Heavyweight Championship]] from Jonnie Stewart. Later that same year, Bundy the reigning AWA heavyweight champion wrestled again headlining an AWA \"Super Event\" at the [[Dee Events Center]] in Ogden, Utah. That night ended differently for Bundy, losing a \"bodyslam match\" to Koszmar Polski who was managed by [[Ken Patera]]. Bundy still wrestled across the country, primarily in the Southern and Eastern United States. He continued to be a headliner and a crowd favorite at all events he attended. King Kong Bundy's last match is thought to have been at the Legends of Wrestling Show at the Pulaski County Fair in Somerset, Kentucky in 2007. Bundy lost to [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] in the main event. In May 2007, Bundy announced his retirement from professional wrestling.<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n\n==Acting career==\nIn 1986, Pallies appeared in television commercials and print advertisements for the [[Philips Computers|Vendex HeadStart]] personal computer.<ref>{{cite web |title=KAYFABE THEATER: King Kong Bundy \u2013 Vendex Computer Commercial \u2014 The Gorilla Position |url=https://classicwrestlingassociation.org/2018/02/02/kayfabe-theater-king-kong-bundy-vendex-computer-commercial-the-gorilla-position/ |website=Classic Wrestling Association |accessdate=March 5, 2019 |language=en |date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBundy had two guest spots and one bit part on ''[[Married... with Children]]'', as the creators had named the lead characters \"Bundy\" as an homage to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/sports/2019/03/king-kong-bundy-married-with-children/|title=King Kong Bundy on 'Married\u2026 With Children' in 1987 & 1995|last=Farrell|first=Paul|date=March 5, 2019|website=Heavy.com|language=en|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In 1987, he played Uncle Irwin, the brother of [[Peggy Bundy]]. In 1995, he appeared again as the King Kong Bundy character, teaching Bud how to wrestle.\n\nIn 1988, he appeared in the [[Richard Pryor]] film ''[[Moving (1988 film)|Moving]]'' as Gorgo, part of a trio of ex-cons who are insolent and careless movers. In 1996, he appeared on an episode of ''[[Weird Science (TV series)|Weird Science]]'' as himself.  He had also appeared on sitcom ''[[Boy Meets World]]''. He is on the cover of Belgian band Belgian Asociality's 2009 album ''Kabaal''.  Bundy had also tried a career in [[stand-up comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007701190320|title=King Kong Bundy puts comedy on the mat tonight at the Colosseum|date=January 18, 2007|publisher=Delaware Online|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223004843/http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007701190320|archivedate=February 23, 2007}}</ref> On April 24, 2008, he was on a [[Norway|Norwegian]] TV show called ''[[Golden Goal (TV series)|Golden GOAL!]]''. Bundy also starred as Otto Belmar in the 2011 independent film ''Fight the Panda Syndicate''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy career==\nAfter retiring from wrestling, Pallies had a brief career run in stand-up comedy, he would perform regularly at various comedy clubs such as the Coffee Dot Comedy in [[Sea Isle City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nj1015.com/the-time-we-taught-king-kong-bundy-standup-comedy/|title=The time we taught King Kong Bundy standup comedy|first=Steve|last=Trevelise|website=New Jersey 101.5|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtxl.com/entertainment/wrestling-star-king-kong-bundy-dies-at-61|title=Wrestling star King Kong Bundy dies at 61|date=March 5, 2019|website=WTXL|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/index/_/id/4707184|title=Chris Pallies aka King Kong Bundy: From wrestling to stand-up comedy - Page 2 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPallies was married, and had a son named David.<ref name=\"NYT Death\" /><ref name=\"WaPo Death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/king-kong-bundy-man-mountain-villain-of-pro-wrestling-dies-at-61/2019/03/05/061dc0dc-3f6a-11e9-a0d3-1210e58a94cf_story.html|title=King Kong Bundy, man-mountain villain of pro wrestling, dies at 63|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Pallies joined a [[class action]] lawsuit filed against WWE which alleged that wrestlers incurred \"long term neurological injuries\" and that the company \"routinely failed to care\" for them and \"fraudulently misrepresented and concealed\" the nature and extent of those injuries.  The suit was litigated by attorney Konstantine Kyros, who has been involved in a number of other lawsuits against WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/breaking/ct-wwe-cte-lawsuit-20160719-story.html|title=Dozens of wrestlers sue WWE over CTE, effects of traumatic brain injuries|last=Bieler|first=Des|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 20, 2016|date=July 19, 2016}}</ref> The case was dismissed by US District Judge [[Vanessa Lynne Bryant]] in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/09/19/lawsuit-against-wwe-concussions-thrown-out/| title= Judge throws out lawsuit against WWE by ex-pro wrestlers over concussions|last=Collins|first=Dave|work= [[The Denver Post]] |accessdate=October 22, 2018| date= September 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPallies was fond of cats and had \u201cabout 10\u201d at the time of his death.<ref name=Romalino>Romalino, Carly Q. \u201c[https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/news/local/south-jersey/2019/03/21/king-kong-bundy-cats-needs-new-homes-wwe-legend/3235987002/ Wrestler King Kong Bundy's cats need new homes]\u201d, The Cherry Hill Courier-Post, March 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nPallies died on March 4, 2019, in [[Glassboro, New Jersey]], at the age of 63 of complications from [[diabetes]].<ref name=\"NYT Death\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mytwintiers.com/sports/18-sports-remembers-king-kong-bundy/|title=18 Sports Remembers King Kong Bundy|date=March 6, 2019|website=WETM - MyTwinTiers.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Film\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Moving (1988 film)|Moving]]''\n|Gorgo\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''Bill's Seat''\n|Big Swede\n|Short film\n|-\n|2010\n|''Card Subject to Change''\n|Himself\n|Documentary film\n|-\n|2011\n|''Fight the Panda Syndicate''\n|Otto Belmar\n|\n|-\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Television\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1987, 1995\n|''[[Married... with Children]]''\n|Uncle Irwin/Himself\n|Episodes: \"All in the Family\", \"Flight of the Bumblebee\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Weird Science (TV series)|Weird Science]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Men in Tights\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Boy Meets World]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Golden Goal (TV series)|Gooden Goal]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2014\n|''The Swerve''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"King Kong Bundy\"\n|}\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Wrestling Superstars Live|AWA Superstars of Wrestling]]'''\n**[[WSL World Heavyweight Championship|AWA Superstars of Wrestling Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WSL World Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''[[Continental Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship|NWA/AWA Southern Heavyweight Championship]]  ([[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n**[[AWA Southern Tag Team Championship|NWA/AWA Southern Tag Team Championship]] ([[AWA Southern Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Rick Rude]]<ref name=SouthernTagBook>{{cite book | first1=Royal |last1=Duncan |first2=Gary |last2=Will | title=Wrestling title histories: professional wrestling champions around the world from the 19th century to the present |location=Waterloo, Ontario |origyear=2000.|chapter= (Memphis, Nashville) Tennessee: Southern Tag Team Title [Roy Welsch & Nick Gulas, Jerry Jarrett from 1977] | pages= 185\u2013189| publisher=Archeus Communications |year=2006 | isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref><ref name=SouthernTagWeb>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/cwa/awa-s-t.html | title=Southern Tag Team Title | work=Wrestling-Titles | accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n*'''[[Georgia Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NWA National Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA National Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Bill Eadie|The Masked Superstar]]\n*'''International Pro Wrestling'''\n**IPW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''International Wrestling Superstars'''\n**IWS United States Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[Maryland Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[MCW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[MCW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''Midwest Championship Wrestling'''\n**MCW Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA New York]]'''\n**[[NWA Continental Heavyweight Championship|NWA New York Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Continental Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 147 of the top 500 wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1995<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1995.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1995|accessdate=March 10, 2019|website=Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 124 of the top 500 wrestlers during the PWI Years in 2003\n*'''Richmond Championship Wrestling'''\n**RCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''Top Rope Wrestling'''\n**TRW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[World Class Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[WCWA World Heavyweight Championship|NWA American Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WCWA World Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=TexAmBook>{{cite book |author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will |title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications |chapter = Texas: NWA / World Class American Heavyweight Title [Von Eric]| pages = 265\u2013266 |year= 2000 |isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref><ref name=US-Am>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tx/wccw/am-h.html | title=NWA United States Heavyweight Title (1967-1968/05) - American Heavyweight Title (1968/05-1986/02) | work=Wrestling-Titles | accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n**[[WCWA World Tag Team Championship|NWA American Tag Team Championship]] ([[WCWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|2 times]]) \u2013 with [[Bill Irwin (wrestler)|Bill Irwin]] (1) and [[Bugsy McGraw]] (1)<ref name=WCCWAmTag>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories |chapter= (Dallas) Texas: NWA American Tag Team Title [Fritz Von Erich] |  publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-9698161-5-7}}</ref><ref name=\"NWAAmericanTag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tx/wccw/am-t.html |title=N.W.A. American Tag Team Title | accessdate=January 19, 2020 |work=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[World Wide Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n**WWWA Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''[[World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n** [[Slammy Award]] (2 times)\n*** [[Bobby Heenan|Bobby \"The Brain\" Heenan]] Scholarship Award ([[Slammy Awards#1987|1987]]) {{small|with [[Tonga Fifita|Haku]], [[Sam Fatu|Tama]], [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], [[Hercules (wrestler)|Hercules]], and [[Harley Race]]}}\n*** Most Evolutionary ([[Slammy Award#1994|1994]]) \u2013 {{small|Tied with [[Gorilla Monsoon]]}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of premature professional wrestling deaths]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WWE superstar}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{The Streak}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bundy, King Kong}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Glassboro, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Washington Township, Gloucester County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling promoters]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Atlantic City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:The First Family (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Heenan Family members]]\n[[Category:The Million Dollar Corporation members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = King Kong Bundy\n|image       = Kingkondbundy.jpg\n|caption     = King Kong Bundy in 1995\n|alt         =\n|birth_name  = Christopher Alan Pallies<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1955|11|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Woodbury, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_place     = [[Glassboro, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2019|03|04|1955|11|7}}\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Marcy Russell|1994|2002|reason=divorced}}\n|children    = 1\n|names       = Big Daddy Bundy<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><br>Boom Boom Bundy<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web |title=King Kong Bundy profile |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/k/king-kong-bundy.html |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref><br>Chris Bundy<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><br>Chris Cannon<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><br>Chris Canyon<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/><ref name=\"Myers1999\"/><br>Crippler Cannon<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>King Kong Bundy<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/><br>Man Mountain Cannon, Jr<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|height      = 6 ft 4 in<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|weight      = 458 lb<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|billed      = [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]]<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/><ref name=\"Shields2010\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|debut       = March 7, 1981<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n|retired     = May 2007<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n}}\n'''Christopher Alan Pallies''' (November 7, 1955 \u2013 March 4, 2019) was an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], actor and [[stand-up comedian]], better known by his [[ring name]], '''King Kong Bundy'''. He appeared in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) in the mid-1980s and mid-1990s and wrestled in the main event of [[WrestleMania 2]] in 1986, facing  [[Hulk Hogan]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage match]] for the [[WWE Championship|WWF World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"Grasso2014\">{{cite book |last=Grasso |first=John |date=2014 |title=Historical Dictionary of Wrestling |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]] |isbn=978-0-8108-7926-3 |pages=55\u201356 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KUsJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 }}</ref><ref name=\"WWEBio\">{{cite web |title=King Kong Bundy |publisher=[[WWE]] |url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/kingkongbundy |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Shields2010\">{{cite book |last=Shields |first=Brian |date=2010 |title=Main Event: WWE in the Raging 80s |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=978-1-4516-0467-2 |pages=80\u201381 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ktv7Nj2C9QUC&pg=PA80}}</ref><ref name=\"Hornbaker2017\">{{cite book |last=Hornbaker |first=Tim |date=2017 |title=Legends of Pro Wrestling: 150 Years of Headlocks, Body Slams, and Piledrivers |publisher=[[Skyhorse Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-61321-875-4 |pages=956\u2013957 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UuGLDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT957}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Woodbury, New Jersey]], on November 7, 1955,<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"NYT Death\">{{cite web |last=Slotnik |first=Daniel E. |date=March 5, 2019 |title=King Kong Bundy, Gargantuan Professional Wrestler, Dies at 63 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/05/obituaries/king-kong-bundy-dead.html |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref> Pallies attended [[Washington Township High School (New Jersey)|Washington Township High School]] in [[Sewell, New Jersey]], graduating in 1973.<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Beym2010\">{{cite web |last=Beym |first=Jessica |date=January 28, 2010 |title=Former professional wrestling star to visit Washington Township to promote hoagie sale |publisher=[[Advance Publications]] |work=[[NJ.com]] |url=http://www.nj.com/gloucester-county/index.ssf/2010/01/former_professional_wrestling.html |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref> He had two sisters and three brothers.<ref name=\"NYT Death\" />\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career (1981\u20131985)===\nPallies was trained to wrestle by [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]] at the \"Monster Factory\" in [[Bellmawr, New Jersey]]. He debuted on March 7, 1981, wrestling for the World Wrestling Federation under the ring name \"Chris Canyon\".<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/><ref name=\"Myers1999\">{{cite book |last=Myers |first=Robert |year=1999 |title=The Professional Wrestling Trivia Book |publisher=Branden Books |isbn=0-8283-2045-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/professionalwres0000myer/page/4 4,49] |url=https://archive.org/details/professionalwres0000myer/page/4 }}</ref> In the early years of his career, he also used the name \"Chris Cannon\".<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Pallies relocated to [[Texas]], where he joined the [[World Class Championship Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Meltzer1986\">{{cite book |last=Meltzer |first=Dave |author-link=Dave Meltzer |year=1986 |title=The Wrestling Observer's Who's who in Pro Wrestling |work=[[Wrestling Observer]] |page=28 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-rFZAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> He was developed by the [[Von Erich family]] as \"Big Daddy Bundy\" (after [[Shirley Crabtree]]'s \"Big Daddy\" moniker).<ref>{{cite web |date=October 7, 2013 |title=The 50 greatest ring names ever |publisher=WWE |url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-greatest-ring-names-ever/page-17 |accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> He wore blue jeans with a rope belt. After a dispute with the Von Erich family, Bundy was recruited by [[Gary Hart (wrestler)|\"Playboy\" Gary Hart]] and dramatically reintroduced as \"King Kong Bundy\", with the \"Big Daddy\" portion of his moniker replaced by the name of cinematic monster, [[King Kong]], wearing the black singlet for the first time to signify his change. He lost his hair during the feud, adding to his signature look.\n\nBundy was [[Fritz Von Erich]]'s opponent for Fritz's 1982 [[Professional wrestling match types#Retirement match|retirement match]] at the [[Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show]] held at the [[Texas Stadium]].<ref name=FritzVonErichRetirement>{{cite web |date=June 4, 1982 |title=Texas Stadium 1982 Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show |publisher=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/misc/wccw/misccards.html#82 |accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=RetirementAlmanak>{{cite news |title=Historical Cards: Fritz Von Erich Retirement Show (June 4, 1982. Irving, Texas) |work=PWI Presents: 2007 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts |publisher=Kappa Publications |id=2007 Edition |page=172}}</ref>\n\nHe also competed in various territories such as the [[American Wrestling Association]] and [[National Wrestling Alliance]]. He also had a tendency to demand a five-count (as opposed to the usual three count) for [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinfalls]] whenever he dominated his opponent in a [[Squash (professional wrestling)|squash]] match, a [[List of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] he began while wrestling for [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Mid-South Wrestling]]. During this time Bundy also wrestled in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] often teaming with [[Rick Rude]] and [[Jim Neidhart]] against opponents such as [[Jerry Lawler]].\n\n===World Wrestling Federation (1985\u20131988)===\n====WWF Championship pursuit (1985\u20131986) ====\n[[File:Andre the Giant.jpg|thumb|Bundy and [[Big John Studd]] facing [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]] and [[Hillbilly Jim]]]]\nAfter making a few appearances on [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]/[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] joint shows in early 1985, Bundy officially debuted in the WWF on the March 16, 1985 airing of ''[[WWF Championship Wrestling]]'', defeating [[Mario Mancini]].<ref name=WWF6389Book>{{cite book |last=Cawthon |first=Graham |year=2013 |title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 1: WWF 1963 - 1989 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1492825975}}</ref> First managed by [[Jimmy Hart]], he was immediately [[Push (professional wrestling)|pushed]] with dominating victories over all of his opponents. Bundy also reprised his gimmick of demanding a five-count from the referee while pinning an opponent, to show how badly he had beaten his hapless opponent.<ref name=WWF6389Book/> He defeated [[Conrad Efraim|S.D. \"Special Delivery\" Jones]] in what was announced as only nine seconds at the [[WrestleMania I|first WrestleMania]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] (it was actually about 17 seconds).<ref name=\"Bundy/Jones\">{{cite web |last=Clapp |first=John |date=April 3, 2012 |title=10 Show of Show Shorties: Return to sender |publisher=[[WWE]] |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/29/fastest-wrestlemania-matches/page-6 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> This remained the shortest match in [[WrestleMania]] history until 2008 when [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] defeated [[Chavo Guerrero Jr.]] in a legitimate eight seconds at [[WrestleMania XXIV]].<ref name=\"slam\">{{cite web |last=Plummer |first=Dale |date=March 30, 2008 |title=Mayweather, Orton survive Mania; Edge, Flair don't |publisher=SLAM! Sports|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/31/5148416.html |accessdate=April 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1985, Hart traded Bundy to manager [[Bobby Heenan]] in exchange for [[Adrian Adonis]] and [[the Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]].<ref name=WWF6389Book/> After joining [[the Heenan Family]], Bundy feuded extensively with [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], a feud which started during an [[List of professional wrestling terms#A|angle]] where Bundy interfered in one of Andr\u00e9's matches and delivered several splashes, giving the Giant a [[kayfabe]] broken [[Human sternum|sternum]].<ref name=WWF6389Book/> They feuded for several months, including a pair of tag team matches on ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event II]]'' and ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event III|III]]'' in late 1985, where Bundy, and Andr\u00e9's other nemesis, [[Big John Studd]], first faced Andr\u00e9 and [[Tony Atlas]] and then Andr\u00e9 and [[WWF World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night's Main Event #2 results |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#2 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night's Main Event #3 results |publisher=Pro Wrestling History |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#3 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> On September 23, 1985, Bundy faced Andr\u00e9 the Giant at [[Madison Square Garden]] in a match billed as \"the Colossal Jostle\". Andr\u00e9 dominated the match, with the match ending after Big John Studd came from the locker rooms to Bundy's aid and attacked the Giant, causing a disqualification.<ref name=HolyGround>{{cite book |last=Cawthon |first=Graham |editor-last=Sawyer |editor-first=Grant |date=November 26, 2014 |title=Holy Ground: 50 Years of WWE at Madison Square Garden (The History of Professional Wrestling) |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-5052292-6-4 |chapter=1980s |pages=130\u2013246}}</ref>\n\nBundy also began targeting Hogan and the WWF World Championship in late 1985. At ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event V]]'', Hogan was dominating challenger [[Don Muraco|the Magnificent Muraco]] when Bundy (with Heenan in tow) ran to ambush Hogan. With Muraco's help, Bundy repeatedly gave Hogan [[Professional wrestling attacks#Body avalanche|avalanches]] and [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big splash|big splash]]es, which caused Hogan to severely bruise his ribs (kayfabe). Bundy demanded a match and claimed Hogan was afraid of him, setting up their [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saturday Night Main Event - Mar. 1, 1986 |publisher=History of WWE |url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/snme.htm |accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> Hogan demanded revenge and agreed to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage]] match for the WWF World Heavyweight Championship as the main event of [[WrestleMania 2]] in the [[Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena|Los Angeles]] portion of the event, which Hogan won.<ref>{{cite web |last=Powell |first=John |title=WrestleMania 2: Caged Heat |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania20/WrestleMania2.html |accessdate=November 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==== Various feuds (1986\u20131988) ====\nLater in 1986, Bundy reformed his tag-team partnership with Studd and began a feud with [[The Machines (professional wrestling)|The Machines]], [[Bill Eadie]] and [[Blackjack Mulligan]] wrestling under masks (as the Super Machine and Big Machine, respectively) and often joined by Andre the Giant (as the Giant Machine). The storyline was that Bundy and Studd, along with Heenan, claimed that the Giant Machine was a masked Andre the Giant, and was competing under the mask and alias to circumvent an earlier suspension (due to no-showing for an event), but none of them ever proved that Andre and the Giant Machine were one and the same. Eventually, Bundy and Studd began teaming up with Heenan in a series of six-man tag team matches against the Machines (usually, Big and Super; as Andre's health was starting to deteriorate at this time, the Giant Machine made occasional appearances, but more often than not, it was either Captain [[Lou Albano]] or a number of popular faces\u2014often, Hogan, [[Roddy Piper]] and others\u2014who teamed with the other Machines). Bundy and Studd were regularly beaten, but won their last match over the Super-Big version of the Machines at Madison Square Garden. Also in the latter half of 1986, Bundy and Studd received shots at the WWF Tag Team Championship against [[The British Bulldogs]], but were unsuccessful, often losing by disqualification. Studd left the WWF shortly after their last match with the Machines, and Bundy went back to singles competition.\n\nAt [[WrestleMania III]], Bundy was involved in a mixed six-man tag team match, teaming up with [[Midget professional wrestler|midget wrestlers]] [[Shigeri Akabane|Little Tokyo]] and [[Eric Tovey|Lord Littlebrook]] against [[Hillbilly Jim]], the [[Raymond Kessler|Haiti Kid]] and [[Lionel Giroux|Little Beaver]]. During the match, after being pestered by Beaver, Bundy body-slammed him and delivered a big elbow, causing his team's disqualification and his own tag partners to turn against him.<ref name=\"WM III\">{{cite news|title=WrestleMania III Results|publisher=WWE|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm3/results/|accessdate=February 14, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Main Event: WWE in the Raging 80s|last=Shields|first=Brian|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2006|isbn=1-4165-3257-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/mainevent00bria/page/81 81]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mainevent00bria/page/81}}</ref> At the [[King of the Ring (1987)|1987 King of the Ring]] on September 4, Bundy made it to the finals of the [[King of the Ring tournament]], where he was defeated by [[Randy Savage]]. In November 1987, Bundy defeated Hulk Hogan via a count-out on an episode of ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XIII]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#13|title=Saturday Night's Main Event #13 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> but lost to Hogan in a rematch on the next episode of the series;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/snme.html#14|title=Saturday Night's Main Event #14 results|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> the match was best known for the referee becoming legitimately injured when he was accidentally caught between Hogan and a charging Bundy, and Andre the Giant's post-match attack of Hogan shortly after Bundy left ringside. Although no longer appearing on the WWF's syndicated TV shows, Bundy continued to wrestle house shows in early 1988 (often losing to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]]); his last match during his initial WWF run was a televised match at [[Madison Square Garden]] in February 1988, teaming up with One Man Gang in a loss to [[Don Muraco]] and [[The Ultimate Warrior]].\n\n=== Semi-retirement (1988\u20131994) ===\nAfter leaving the WWF in 1988, Bundy went into semi-retirement, wrestling only a handful of matches. In 1993, he wrestled in the main event of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]]'s inaugural [[November to Remember#1993|November to Remember]] [[Card (sports)#Supercard|supercard]], appearing as the mystery tag team partner of [[Terry Funk]] in a losing effort against [[Road Warrior Hawk]] and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]]. On May 13, 1994, Bundy defeated [[The Godfather (wrestler)|Papa Shango]] at NWA New Jersey. In the summer of 1994 he made a couple of appearances for [[United States Wrestling Association]].\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation (1994\u20131995) ===\nBundy returned to the WWF in the fall of 1994 as a member of [[Ted DiBiase]]'s [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Stable|stable]], [[The Million Dollar Corporation]].<ref name=WWF9099Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 2: WWF 1990 - 1999  | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2013 | asin=B00RWUNSRS}}</ref><ref name=\"Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/m/million-dollar-corporation.html|title=Million Dollar Corporation profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> He had a successful [[pay-per-view]] return at the [[Survivor Series (1994)|Survivor Series]], when he and fellow \"Million Dollar Team\" member Bam Bam Bigelow survived a match against [[Lex Luger]]'s \"Guts and Glory\" team.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Bundy was then billed as a favorite in the [[Royal Rumble (1995)|1995 Royal Rumble]], but lasted only three minutes before being eliminated by another big man, [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Rumble 1995 Elimination Info|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble2.html#95|accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> Bundy made his return to WrestleMania at [[WrestleMania XI]], where [[Undefeated WrestleMania streak of The Undertaker|he was defeated]] by [[the Undertaker]],<ref name=WWF9099Book/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Wrestlemania20/WrestleMania11.html|title=No worse WrestleMania than 11|author=Powell, John|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=November 8, 2009}}</ref> Bundy was later pushed down the card before being released in October 1995 after teaming with [[The Godfather (wrestler)|Kama]] losing to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] and [[Henry O. Godwinn]] for a dark match for [[WWF Superstars of Wrestling]].\n\n===Independent circuit and retirement (1995\u20132007)===\n{{more|Heroes of Wrestling}}\nAfter leaving the WWF in late 1995,<ref name=WWF9099Book/> Bundy wrestled for several independent promotions in the United States. In April 1997, he resurfaced in magazines when he joined a faction managed by [[Kenny Casanova]] called \"Camp Casanova\" along with \"Danger\" Dave DeJohn and the Masked Maniac at times in USWF, NBW, and USA Power Pro Wrestling. In a match against \"the Seven Foot Tall\" Primo Canera III, Bundy knee-dropped his opponent and then \"Bundy-splashed\" him. The impact actually broke the ring, leaving the two grapplers in a pit in the center of the squared circle. This independent footage was picked up by ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]''.\n\nHis feuds against [[Jimmy Snuka|\"Superfly\" Jimmy Snuka]], [[Doink the Clown]], and [[Tom Brandi]] were among many main events in the northeast independent circuit. In 1999, at the Kolf Arena in [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]] he won the [[WSL World Heavyweight Championship|AWA Superstars of Wrestling Heavyweight Championship]] from Jonnie Stewart. Later that same year, Bundy the reigning AWA heavyweight champion wrestled again headlining an AWA \"Super Event\" at the [[Dee Events Center]] in Ogden, Utah. That night ended differently for Bundy, losing a \"bodyslam match\" to Koszmar Polski who was managed by [[Ken Patera]]. Bundy still wrestled across the country, primarily in the Southern and Eastern United States. He continued to be a headliner and a crowd favorite at all events he attended. King Kong Bundy's last match is thought to have been at the Legends of Wrestling Show at the Pulaski County Fair in Somerset, Kentucky in 2007. Bundy lost to [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] in the main event. In May 2007, Bundy announced his retirement from professional wrestling.<ref name=\"Grasso2014\"/>\n\n==Acting career==\nIn 1986, Pallies appeared in television commercials and print advertisements for the [[Philips Computers|Vendex HeadStart]] personal computer.<ref>{{cite web |title=KAYFABE THEATER: King Kong Bundy \u2013 Vendex Computer Commercial \u2014 The Gorilla Position |url=https://classicwrestlingassociation.org/2018/02/02/kayfabe-theater-king-kong-bundy-vendex-computer-commercial-the-gorilla-position/ |website=Classic Wrestling Association |accessdate=March 5, 2019 |language=en |date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBundy had two guest spots and one bit part on ''[[Married... with Children]]'', as the creators had named the lead characters \"Bundy\" as an homage to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/sports/2019/03/king-kong-bundy-married-with-children/|title=King Kong Bundy on 'Married\u2026 With Children' in 1987 & 1995|last=Farrell|first=Paul|date=March 5, 2019|website=Heavy.com|language=en|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In 1987, he played Uncle Irwin, the brother of [[Peggy Bundy]]. In 1995, he appeared again as the King Kong Bundy character, teaching Bud how to wrestle.\n\nIn 1988, he appeared in the [[Richard Pryor]] film ''[[Moving (1988 film)|Moving]]'' as Gorgo, part of a trio of ex-cons who are insolent and careless movers. In 1996, he appeared on an episode of ''[[Weird Science (TV series)|Weird Science]]'' as himself.  He had also appeared on sitcom ''[[Boy Meets World]]''. He is on the cover of Belgian band Belgian Asociality's 2009 album ''Kabaal''.  Bundy had also tried a career in [[stand-up comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007701190320|title=King Kong Bundy puts comedy on the mat tonight at the Colosseum|date=January 18, 2007|publisher=Delaware Online|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223004843/http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007701190320|archivedate=February 23, 2007}}</ref> On April 24, 2008, he was on a [[Norway|Norwegian]] TV show called ''[[Golden Goal (TV series)|Golden GOAL!]]''. Bundy also starred as Otto Belmar in the 2011 independent film ''Fight the Panda Syndicate''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy career==\nAfter retiring from wrestling, Pallies had a brief career run in stand-up comedy, he would perform regularly at various comedy clubs such as the Coffee Dot Comedy in [[Sea Isle City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nj1015.com/the-time-we-taught-king-kong-bundy-standup-comedy/|title=The time we taught King Kong Bundy standup comedy|first=Steve|last=Trevelise|website=New Jersey 101.5|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtxl.com/entertainment/wrestling-star-king-kong-bundy-dies-at-61|title=Wrestling star King Kong Bundy dies at 61|date=March 5, 2019|website=WTXL|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/index/_/id/4707184|title=Chris Pallies aka King Kong Bundy: From wrestling to stand-up comedy - Page 2 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPallies was married, and had a son named David.<ref name=\"NYT Death\" /><ref name=\"WaPo Death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/king-kong-bundy-man-mountain-villain-of-pro-wrestling-dies-at-61/2019/03/05/061dc0dc-3f6a-11e9-a0d3-1210e58a94cf_story.html|title=King Kong Bundy, man-mountain villain of pro wrestling, dies at 63|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Pallies joined a [[class action]] lawsuit filed against WWE which alleged that wrestlers incurred \"long term neurological injuries\" and that the company \"routinely failed to care\" for them and \"fraudulently misrepresented and concealed\" the nature and extent of those injuries.  The suit was litigated by attorney Konstantine Kyros, who has been involved in a number of other lawsuits against WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/breaking/ct-wwe-cte-lawsuit-20160719-story.html|title=Dozens of wrestlers sue WWE over CTE, effects of traumatic brain injuries|last=Bieler|first=Des|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 20, 2016|date=July 19, 2016}}</ref> The case was dismissed by US District Judge [[Vanessa Lynne Bryant]] in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/09/19/lawsuit-against-wwe-concussions-thrown-out/| title= Judge throws out lawsuit against WWE by ex-pro wrestlers over concussions|last=Collins|first=Dave|work= [[The Denver Post]] |accessdate=October 22, 2018| date= September 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPallies was fond of cats and had \u201cabout 10\u201d at the time of his death.<ref name=Romalino>Romalino, Carly Q. \u201c[https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/news/local/south-jersey/2019/03/21/king-kong-bundy-cats-needs-new-homes-wwe-legend/3235987002/ Wrestler King Kong Bundy's cats need new homes]\u201d, The Cherry Hill Courier-Post, March 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nPallies died on March 4, 2019, in [[Glassboro, New Jersey]], at the age of 63 of complications from [[diabetes]].<ref name=\"NYT Death\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mytwintiers.com/sports/18-sports-remembers-king-kong-bundy/|title=18 Sports Remembers King Kong Bundy|date=March 6, 2019|website=WETM - MyTwinTiers.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Film\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Moving (1988 film)|Moving]]''\n|Gorgo\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''Bill's Seat''\n|Big Swede\n|Short film\n|-\n|2010\n|''Card Subject to Change''\n|Himself\n|Documentary film\n|-\n|2011\n|''Fight the Panda Syndicate''\n|Otto Belmar\n|\n|-\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Television\n|-style=\"bac